      <hedline>
        <hl1>Summing Up: Is Our House Divided by Race?; Young, Black, in Prison</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gabe Krichheimer letter says anyone who believes that America has made real progress in reducing racial discrimination cannot be aware that 11 percent of young black men are in prison or jail</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Poll Finds Optimistic Outlook but Enduring Racial Division'' (front page, July 11):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Poll Finds Optimistic Outlook but Enduring Racial Division'' (front page, July 11):</p>
        <p>Anyone who believes that America has made ''real progress'' in reducing racial discrimination cannot be aware that according to the Justice Department, 11 percent of young black men are in prison or jail.</p>
        <p>Opportunity and justice do not favor the less affluent black population. Blacks are not born criminals, and the greater society must acknowledge and rectify this tragic situation for equality to become reality.</p>
        <p>GABE KIRCHHEIMER  New York, July 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
